< user>
108429625033534225531</user>
<name>Vinh Nguyen<//name>< date>
1575740990348< /date>
< rate>
4<//rate>
< Review>
Place is hidden away from plain view but is the epitome of hole in the wall Mexican food joint! It's a hidden gem.

Got the carne asada fries, small order. Look at that size! Most places would give you a lot less.

The thin cut fries were cooked well and carne asada is flavorful and well done. Comes with cheese, sour cream, guac and cotija. If you're from San Diego you'd know most joints won't give you both sour cream and guac so I was pleasantly surprised.

This is the classic San Diegan carne asada fries and you won't be disappointed! Hot sauce was flavorful as well. They do have an extra  spicy jalapeno hot sauce that's perfectly complements the fries.</Review>

Been going there since 2013 and my top picks are Chile Verde Burrito, Breakfast Burrito, or Carne Asada Fries. Sometimes I call ahead of time or order in person, or I send my friend to get the food. Today 4/4/17 I decided to call ahead, and its been a while I hvnt been there. I tried to order Chile Verde burrito and the girl stated that there's no such thing,only the plate option. I was confused,  she said they have never made any Chile Verde "burrito". Ended driving over and talk to them in person, so apparently both the girl taking orders and the chef guy are NEW employees. So I told them I've always order the burrito. Took me sometime to convince them, at the end I got my Chile Verde Burrito!! .. no bad arguments happened, I think they did great w costumers service. For that I had to tip them.. so I give them 5 stars!< /review>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
I guess I could say the absolute only complaint I have about this place is that there's really nothing to complain about. When it comes to self-serve car washes there's only two types of places ones where everything is broken and it really doesn't get your car clean at all and then there's Denny's. Everything installed I was in work, I had zero problems with anything. And my work van looks amazing. I realize I'm doing all the work, I realize I'm getting wet if I'm not careful, but you know what there's something very satisfying about washing my car by hand. Doing the work myself. And you know what I saved a lot of money compared to a traditional car wash. There's going to come point your car is going to need to be washed. That's just the nature of owning one. Save yourself some money, be willing to put in a little bit effort, and you will be rewarded with a completely clean and beautiful looking vehicle.< /Review>

<Date>1620838942333</Date><text>Not as good as the other car washes I've used.  I have a ford transit, 9ft high, and I need the stairs to reach the top of the car. This car wash had the one with the stairs but only for one side so it was very difficult to get the top of the car cleaned. I'm short so I couldn't really reach with the brush. There was no soap coming out of the brush and the brush itself didn't really help with taking off the dirt.  On the plus side this car wash had an air blower to assist with drying.  The vacuum part of the wash was cheaper than where I usually go but it didn't have the aromatic option.  This wash was on the way to an appt I had and I had time to get my car washed but I would not go again. I feel my car still needs a good wash.</text></record>

<text>This food was incredible! I will definitely be back. We came for a weekend trip and decided to have Sunday brunch on the warf. Best decision ever. The food presentation was artistic and Beautiful! The aroma was incredible. The smoked trout was to die for. It was smoothe and buttery in texture and the smoke on it was perfect. The crab bisque was creamy and had a smokey flavor to it which I loved.  The clams in the chowder were very tender and fresh which we enjoyed with the deliciousand fresh sourdough. My favorite dish however was the Salmon and crab cake Benedict. My eggs were cooked to perfection and the cake was the best I have ever had. There is definitely something to be said about eating fresh seafood right on the warf. The only thing that could have made my experience better would have been to watch the fishing boats unloading at the docks but it was Sunday. We did however get a lovely visit from a few Sea Lions. Couldn't have asked for a better experience on our trip.<//text>< pictures>

<Rate>5</Rate><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMxobWiZVrGn-BW3PWXJi1OBJQn01kVtY671sJ_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMXizY-ffsygf9kv3YMeBO8_6o9pd1KRvpKlnBM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< Text>
Excellent quick service, I had a reservation but was able to be seated sooner than our appointed time. The food was fresh,not surprised since we are right by the water. Fried calamari had a perfect consistency of batter, texture and flavor. I had to try the crab cake sandwich, I was not disappointed in the moist and crispy cake on a beautiful brioche bun they served me. I had a crack in my glass, I alerted the waiter to prevent any accidents/messes, he replaced the glass and beverage right away. I had to pass on the dessert, I was much too full to proceed. I recommend this place to anyone trying to have a peaceful dinner with terrific service. The price is also great for the quality of food.</Text>

Amazing food. Friendly service.

My friend and I sat at the bar and had a marvelous experience. The bartender Kyler couldn't be friendlier. He recommended the right tequilas and meal.

< review>
A San Francisco institution that has adapted with the times. Kudos to Scoma‚Äôs for keeping the show going with great to go food and beverage. The out door dining options are really great now, especially if the weather is nice. The hosts, bartenders, wait staff and kitchen are all very kind and smiling. The food quality is really great and the prices are reasonable. Always fresh amazing g quality fish and seafood. The chowder and crab bisque are amazing. The calamari is a favorite. The sourdough is on point. Make sure to stop by especially if the weather is nice. Make a rez if you don‚Äôt want to wait but waiting around with a drink soaking in the scene ain‚Äôt so bad. Food favorites - definitely recommend the crab cakes and clam chowder! Both were amazing.

Experience - staff was really friendly and it was so nice to sit outside and enjoy the views. The patio is dog friendly which was perfect for our pup! Service was a little slow at times but we were busy most of the time in good company.

Price - coming from Chicago I thought things were slightly overpriced here, even for seafood but maybe that‚Äôs normal to the area.

Overall would recommend!< /review>

<Text>Made reservations online for this well-respected joint. Wanted a drink, maybe a snack.

Upon arrival, we were snottily informed that they don't do reservations for drinks. We were sat in a disused section, apparently the "seats of shame".

As we sat and sipped our drinks (15 minutes of a wait for those), we watched the main outdoor dining section. Not only was it not full, but it continued to empty as we sat.

Had the front desk jockey been kinder, we would have had more to drink and even snacks. Who knew that restaurants would be in a hurry to mistreat customers after being closed for so long?< /Text>< Pics>

My favorite dish however was the Salmon and crab cake Benedict. My eggs were cooked to perfection and the cake was the best I have ever had. There is definitely something to be said about eating fresh seafood right on the warf. The only thing that could have made my experience better would have been to watch the fishing boats unloading at the docks but it was Sunday. We did however get a lovely visit from a few Sea Lions. Couldn't have asked for a better experience on our trip.< /Review>< pics>

< Review>
A San Francisco institution that has adapted with the times. Kudos to Scoma‚Äôs for keeping the show going with great to go food and beverage. The out door dining options are really great now, especially if the weather is nice. The hosts, bartenders, wait staff and kitchen are all very kind and smiling. The food quality is really great and the prices are reasonable. Always fresh amazing g quality fish and seafood. The chowder and crab bisque are amazing. The calamari is a favorite. Wonderful date place! <user_id>104830388093091509737<//user_id>< user_name>
Joy<//user_name>
< time>
1600844295713< /time>
<rate>4</rate><text>It had been over six months since I had had a meal at a restaurant or made a reservation. With the sun shining, the idea of enjoying a cold crab salad overlooking the water appealed to me. Plus it's a nice image thinking of Al Scoma creating a family business 50+ years ago and having a pier named after him. Could such a story unfold for a scrappy go-getter these days?

We were a few minutes early for our lunch reservation, so we took the time to enjoy the view of the water and the mosaic ode to the city outside. Definitely easy to appreciate on a warm day. A few minutes later, we were seated at a picnic style table and received sourdough bread and whipped butter, and glasses of ice water.

Unfortunately, one of the glasses had remnants of red lipstick on it. We brought it to our server's attention, and later on, he replaced our water. Without a word, he took the glass and walked away. I couldn't help thinking it would have been nice if he had shown some sign of remorse. I understand that dishwashers can leave behind residue, but given these especially germaphobic times, a little sign of concern for the patrons from the staff goes a long way.

$13 Crab Bisque Bowl:
This orange bowl had a creamy tomato flavor with chunks of crab meat, topped with chives and cracked pepper.

$21 Scoma's Dungeness Crab Cake:
A pair of lightly battered and fried crab medallions were served with a small portion of arugula salad on the side and some creamy dipping salad. The crab was still chunky, which was definitely a plus, because that definitely beats crab cakes with pulverized crab mush.

$47 Scoma's Crab Louis Salad "Classic" 1/2 lb:
I knew the Crab Louis was going to be a large portion, even with the smaller "Classic" sized portion, but when I saw the plate set down in front of me, I knew we would have leftovers. The pile of crab meat sat on top of shredded lettuce, decked out with juicy heirloom tomatoes, cucumber slices, a boiled egg, bell peppers, carrots, olives, lemon wedges, and a ramekin overflowing with Louis dressing. It was cool and refreshing, not to mention the crab and the accoutrements were sweet and satisfying. My only complaint was I would have preferred if the carrot were peeled, because the outer layers looked a touch hairy.
I happily packed up the leftovers and looked forward to digging into it for my next meal. Our server joked that we did a good effort, but ate too much of the salad, haha.

I thoroughly enjoyed the food, and I probably would have enjoyed it even more if I had the opportunity to witness seeing the 'Pier to Plate' process unfold. I would rate my experience a 7/10, and would be more of a solid 4/5 had it not been for the dirty glasses. I wish I could say that I will save myself the money and make my own Crab Louis, but I sure do appreciate someone else shelling all that crab.<//text>< Pics>

Service was great. <rate>5</rate><Text>A great restaurant a little off the beaten path on Fisherman's Wharf. That is they own their own boats and seafood processing facility across the street. Excellent seafood prepared extremely well! By the way they also make craft cocktails including a Bloody Mary made with house made gin. There are so many places to choose from but even at lunch hour in the middle of the week, this restaurant is very busy. Scoma's was recommended by our cabbie a lifelong resident of San Francisco. <Time>1605013616291<//Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
With so many of the iconic restaurants in the heart of the tourist area closed I was lucky to find Scoma. Sat indoors in the dining room. It was intimate and well appointed. Service!  This was old world service. I can't remember the last time I had service this attentive to detail and my dining experience. The food was excellent. The dining selection is broad and the Chardonnay I selected was perfect. The food was excellent. Scallops were expertly seared, shrimp cocktail was delicious, risotto was just right, dessert snd coffee were an indulgent experience. I loved the entire experience and highly recommend this treasure just steps away from the commercial clatter of the high traffic tourist spots.</Review>

<Date>1604021991918< /Date><Rating>1<//Rating>< text>
My girlfriend and I were visiting SF and in one place this restaurant was highly recommended to us.  It was a shame to have such a bad experience despite how beautiful this place looks.  The first thing was the poor attention of the waitress, she took the order three meters away, I had to choose a little voice to take my order, besides that she had no interest in explaining the menus well.  Then my girlfriend asked for a salmon and it was raw, this situation was very unpleasant, they offered us to reconcile it but she did not want to continue eating, not even the waitress herself apologized.  not if all this had to do with the time I decided to go, it was like 8:00 pm.  My girlfriend went to the bathroom and it was very dirty.  the truth is that all this is a shame for this well located place.  Hopefully it will improve a bit since the services are not cheap at all, I find it expensive and of very low quality.  I think I would think twice to return here.<//text>

<userid>107909243264727992414< /userid><name>Cathy Perez</name><date>1557790901617<//date><rating>5<//rating>< text>
A friend suggested this restaurant to me and I'm so glad she did! First of all, the staff was amazing. They were very friendly and, helpful with suggestions.
Had an amazing margarita to start and had the trio for 2 as an appetizer which includes, calamari, crabcakes and bacon wrapped scallops. Now I am usually not a fan of seafood beyond calamari but the crabcakes were amazing and came with a delicious dipping sauce. Also had a delicious caesar salad.
I had the filet as an entree with asparagus with lemon and it was cooked perfectly and tasted delicious. One of the best dinners I've had in quite a while.< /text>

<Text>Very fresh seafood that they say is sourced from the local fishermen and fisheries. They're generous with the butter and everything is consistent. The first time I came here, I had the louie salad, which was extremely basic. My latest return I tried out their seafood pastas and it was so rich I could die. Definitely something you need lots of bread for, but worth trying. Interior is a little bit nautical and storied with the waiters being attentive and checking in often. [{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOg-OyERqJFhppcdy-iLZfCele-xgexSfWBrqau=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>

<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPPzbuaNW6XdH-9vZv7OK7Ua68H6sTBcph0K5oI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOU0QN-EM1ahK7WtHVTRWwppnmpKsOeb3ctgRUQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO24uVdx6eUhPskrWK_syLnaN0AMvsZEN8J-3jA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmap_id>< Review>
On a work trip after a full day. We ate dinner here. It was one of the few dining options available to get us out of our hotel room.

They had extra tables setup where parking used to be. So we ate outside. The view was awesome. The service was top notch.

Drinks. Delicious. I had the smoked maple old fashioned. My dining mate (and friend and coworker) had a Southern Comfort and 7up.

Dinner (we couldn't fit dessert) was the grilled king salmon over Scomaronia and the Cioppino.

We ordered a couple apps too. Dungeness crab, oysters and shrimp. All good. All gone.

We so enjoyed our dinner here!

Thank you team Scoma!!

Hopefully you are able to get a new boat soon!!<//Review>

5< /rate>
< Text>
I was looking for a nice place to eat on the bay, but the restaurants on Fisherman's Wharf looked way too touristic to me. I opted for this more hidden restaurant and I've been positively surprised. First, the staff is super friendly and welcoming. Then the atmosphere, very "marine" with all the wood. Last but not least, the food is great! Fresh fish from the bay, with many different options available. Wasn't expecting this quality. Sure, is not the cheapest option around, but if you want to eat well this i's the place to go!< /Text>

<user_id>104412019682023142160< /user_id>< user_name>
Stefanie Ulrey<//user_name>
<Date>1592017903277<//Date><rating>1</rating>< review>
I would give this place NO STARS if the site would let me!

Up until tonight, I always loved this place. In fact, I had made a commitment to patronize local restaurants that remained open during the Shelter in Place order to help them during this crisis. Scoma's was one of those places. I had ordered "curbside delivery" a couple of times, no problem. Drive up, someone comes out, takes your card, goes inside and runs the check, and then comes right back with your bill to sign and your bag of food. And away you go. I might add that the service was always masked and gloved.

So tonight, I called in an order, arrived in my car at the time I said I would be there. Someone was there to tell me where to park, and there I sat with absolutely no acknowledgement from the staff inside for the next 15 minutes! Meanwhile, there was a birthday party going on right in front of me, and they received two full food deliveries while I was sitting there!

The same parking guy walked by again and I finally got his attention. He went in to check on my order, and a girl came and informed me that I had to COME INSIDE AND PAY to get my order - OH REALLY? SINCE WHEN? What happened to the "curbside delivery" that you have advertised on your website, and that I've patronized at least twice without any problem? She then informed me that it was because I called my order in rather than ordering online - RIGHT! I called my orders before without any problems, so I knew that wasn't it. She finally admitted that they were busy - evidently too busy to handle the transaction as advertised. OK, well then I'm too busy to be your customer! I told her to skip it and drove away without my order.

So this is how you treat your neighborhood patrons who were loyal to you during the SIP? Suddenly the SIP order's relaxed and  you're letting people into your restaurant to order and pay, and people are standing around in the parking lot, less than six feet apart and no masks, partying and getting all your service. I see. And now I hope some of my neighbors will see, too. SHAME ON YOU. If that's how you're going to treat loyal customers, then you will never get my business again. SHAME. ON. YOU!< /review>
<pics>None< /pics>< Resp>

We looked into what happened there and unfortunately it was a perfect storm of getting slammed and not having the proper training for the staff that was on hand at the time. We do happily offer curbside service and do handle the transactions as advertised. It will not happen again. Next time you order or come by, please introduce yourself so we can apologize in person and make sure you have a 100% perfect experience. Thank you and we look forward to serving you again."}</Resp>

<Rate>1< /Rate><text>This restaurant shares the pier with fishing boats (that also pay rent) and park here so that we can all get fresh fish. It's a pier after all. {'time': 1592089091527, 'text': 'Catherine, please know Scoma\'s is perhaps the biggest supporter of the local fishing fleet in the entire city. We are more than happy to have any fishing boat being on the pier and several do. We have been letting FV Pioneer sell seafood in our parking lot, which we pay for, at no cost to them. We have no ability, desire or authority to put anyone out of business, and the Pioneer could easily move to a different slip if it wanted to.\n\nIt is an unfortunate situation but we have well over 100 employees, many local fishing crews and countless farmers whose livelihoods depend on our being able to conduct business. After offering several solutions to the FV Pioneer no agreement could be reached.\n\nPlease read this unbiased statement from the Port of San Francisco if you are interested in knowing the facts of the situation.\n\nThank you for your feedback we we hope this response and the Port\'s statement below gives you clarity on the situation.\n\nStatement issued by the Port of San Francisco yesterday:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\n\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\n\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\n\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nFor additional information please contact the Port of San Francisco Public Affairs Office.'}< /Response>
<gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34</gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<user_name>Scott<//user_name><text>I'm a local, and I eat on the San Francisco waterfront often. This is definitely one of the best meals I've had near the Pier 39 / fisherman's wharf area.

Fried calamari was very good, although it could have been just a touch more crispy.

Crispy fries with truffle oil and parmesan cheese were out of this world.

The beet salad was small for the price, but tasted amazing.

The bread roll tasted fresh, but it was not warm.

Service was fast and friendly. I was dining alone and I got one of the tables facing out toward the fishing boats.

The location makes this one of those places that you will not stumble onto. You must see the sign and walk toward the Bay down the pier.

The restaurant is like time stopped in 1965, but it's clean and well-maintained inside.

food is expensive, but not over-the-top expensive. I ordered three appetizers, calamari, crispy fries, and the beet salad. And with two diet Pepsi's it came to $51, before tip.

I will definitely be back here.< /text><pics>None</pics>< response>
None<//response>

We have been coming to Scoma's during family visits to San Francisco practically since the restaurant opened in 1965. The setting on the wharf is very special, and the jacketed waiters are exactly the way I remember them back in the 1960s.  They are also very helpful and efficient! Paul Sutherland<//user_name>
<date>1549937191321< /date>< rating>
5</rating>
< review>
In my opinion this has to be one of the best restaurants in the US. Tucked away down a small street at Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco, Scoma's is like finding buried treasure. The restaurant itself is not overly ostentatious but the warm friendly staff make you feel imediately welcome.
I tried out Fettucine ‚ÄúPomodori Secchi e Pollo‚Äù. Now I have eaten Pasta dishes in around 16 countries, including Milan, Italy. I have to say, this was the best chicken pasta dish I have ever tasted. It was sublime. Its no surprise, whereever you look that this particular restaurant has reviews of 4.5 stars and over. My rating is a full 5* and that it is my number 1 restaurant in the US so far. If you are ever in the area don't miss an opportunity to pay Scoma's a visit.</review>

< userid>
115841246477616920126</userid>
< Name>
Kevin Grim< /Name>
<Time>1505453547124<//Time><rating>5< /rating>< text>
Before going on our honeymoon, we were told by several people that all the places to eat at or around fisherman's wharf are essentially the same...while that isn't a bad thing, the sole exception is Scoma's. While all the seafood around the wharf is likely fresh, at Scoma's not only do you know it is but the service and preparation they put into each meal is unmatched. Our server dutifully told us exactly which dishes were locally caught and prepared fresh vs frozen. I started with the clam chowder and can honestly say it was one of the best I ever had. For entrees, my wife and I had the locally caught, fresh blackened cod.  Perfectly cooked and spiced, it was so good, I had to slow myself down to enjoy it more...as well as stop myself from just going caveman on it and eating it with my bare hands. Also, as a bonus, our awesome waiter (who had previously asked what brought us to San Fran after learning that we lived in NJ) brought us some incredible sorbet and ice cream to congratulate us on our marriage/honeymoon. This added an entire new level to our experience. When we are in San Fran again, we will definitely be returning!</text>

<Date>1556431014458</Date><Text>Let me start by saying coming from NY especially near many Italian and seafood inspired places I came in with very high expectations. < text>
Food is a 5 star.  Was excellent and the service was excellent as well.  Again 5 stars.  So why a 3 star rating.  I was seated in a small room in the back of the restaurant.  Attached to this room with no separation was a waiter service area.  You know coffee makers, drink machines.   Wasn't too bad until they started bussing table in the larger dining room and walking though the small dining room.  Then making a lot of racket racking and stacking dirty dishes.   If I wanted a nice view of a food prep area with a lot of noise I would have gone to Denny's.  I didn't complain during the meal as it was my wife's birthday and I didn't want to upset her my complaining.

With that said, food is good just watch out where they seat you.< /text>

{'time': 1592014141885, 'text': 'Vol, it seems like you are referring to the issue FV Pioneer has brought up. Please know Scoma\'s has long been one of, if not the biggest supporters of the local fishing fleet, including FV Pioneer. Below is a statement from the Port of San Francisco outlining the facts of the situation:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nThank you for your interest and please contact the Port of San Francisco if you have any questions regarding this situation.'}<//Resp>

< text>
Discovered this place while visiting San Francisco. It is just off the main drag, so it is easy to miss, if you aren't looking for it, specifically. That is a good thing. The restaurant is quieter and much higher quality food than the places among the main road. The history behind this place is fascinating.

The seafood is fresh caught and delicious.

The staff was very friendly.

I did not have a reservation, but I arrived early enough that I only had about a 20 minute wait. Call ahead if you want to guarantee a timely seat.

I will definitely go back next time im in the city.< /text>

<rating>4< /rating><pictures>None</pictures>< review>
We have been coming to Scomas for decades. We moved away from CA to N. Carolina, so we came to eat on a visit back. The food was fantastic and our service was impeccable as always. We asked for special orders from the old menu, which they made for us. I am glad they are now committed to sustainability, but the prices had gone up a lot and the portion sizes have gone down. The price increase, along with the smaller portions is the reason for 4 stars rather than 5. I can see one or the other, but not both. The price increase for the seafood saute was 30%!</review>

I was conducting my San Francisco Photo Tours for my Florida clients and a Lyft Driver recommended Scoma's for the best clam chowder in San Francisco. The restaurant was hard to find but we finally found it. Service was real slow when we arrive like 9 pm. It was busy and we finally got our clam chowder. <Rate>1<//Rate>< review>
I'm genuinely confused by how highly rated this is. Even for the fisherman's wharf or Pier 39, the food was pretty terrible. The clam chowder was alright if you could overcome the grittiness of what I assumed was poorly cleaned clams. I will say that the truffle fries were good, but slightly oily. I got the petrale dore, which was recommended by our waiter, and it was absolutely horrible. I would not recommend this dish unless you like to pay $35 for oily, deep fried cardboard. The only redeeming thing on the plate was the tartar sauce, but that wasn't enough to cover the horrendous taste of the petrale. When I told the staff who took my staff that I didn't want leftovers a sit was just not good, nothing was done about it. Seriously, make the trek to Woodhouse, Waterbar, or anywhere on the grotto if you want good seafood.< /review>

Top notch service beginning with hostess and host...so friendly and professional- sorry to the two of you but the service was so spot on that we didn't have time to get your names! < Name>
Yael Rootberg<//Name>
<Time>1416592459381< /Time><Rate>5</Rate>< text>
I visited in June of 2014. It took me a bit to get past the dated decor...

It was a little hard for a first timer to San Francisco to find, but turned out to be a hidden gem.

The food was absolutely out of this world. Dishes were spot on. Some of the best and freshest seafood I have tasted anywhere. Pasta was cooked perfectly (not over done like most places will serve).  Sauces tasted fresh.

This was the first restaurant I visited on my first visit to San Francisco, and it set the bar high for my expectations of the quality of seafood for the area. Some restaurants came close but none matched.

I would highly recommend this restaurant!< /text>

< Rate>

<Text>I was taken to this restaurant for my anniversary.  Believe me when I say I tried to get out of it.  I didn't want to sit in a restaurant that smelled of fish or had creatures swimming awaiting their doom.  So I balked all the way to San Francisco.  When we arrived I thought it's a "Hole in the Wall" from the area we had driven into.  Then a valet came to park the car which I found odd because the restaurant appeared very small from the outside.
Boy, was I fooled.

Inside, you have a reservation counter and a cozy waiting place upstairs with vintage pictures on the wall.  There may be a 30 - 45 minute wait but you are not uncomfortable.  Drinks may be ordered from the waiting area and it's not drafty.  Upon going to the dining room, the doors were slid back and what a view!  Elegant dining room with a back wall view of the bay.  Service was on point and at the time Walter was my server.  He was the most charming man ever.  I had the Lobster Provolone Dinner and it was hands-down 5 star!  We had a Lovely evening.

Two weeks later in-laws from Germany arrived and after hearing about Scoma's took us out to this restaurant.  We all had a delightful time and this is now my favorite restaurant.  The crab salad is a must!  One salad fed 4 adults and we were almost too full for the meal.  Excellent!  10 Star!!< /Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< resp>
None< /resp>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
This is my favorite place to dine in San Francisco. We always get the Cioppino, which only gets better each time we eat here. It is off the beaten path a little , built on it's own little Wharf shared with working fishing vessels so all the sights, sounds and smells are there. (A disclaimer...smells like the sea, not dead fish....inside it smells like wonderful cooking üòÄ). The wait staff is extrodinary. They have all been there for, I kid you not, for decades. I feel this place has not changed much since it opened....they know what is good and they keep doing great food.<//text>

< Rate>

< text>
Classic white tablecloth Californian seafood restaurant, with professional table service, fresh fish and a good enough bar. The plancha seared calamari were really good and I also had the crab Thermidor and shared crab plate and both were fine. People here are a mixture of tourists and adult old time Californians and the menu is the traditional old time french inspired seafood cuisine. It's a five stars if you are really into that, otherwise it's a little bit expensive for what they offer.</text>

I've never eaten at fisherman's wharf but on my last trip I couldn't avoid it. Scoma's was probably there before fisherman's wharf turned into the tourist trap it is today. <userid>110444854147788105330</userid><Gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /Gmap_id>< Review>
Nothing was particularly wrong, but nothing was spectacular either. We tried Scoma's based on several recommendations by friends. Our waitress was great, very attentive and knowledgeable about the menu. We order drinks to start while deciding what to eat, the drinks were delivered quickly, they're fine...a little light on the alcohol based on how much they're charging and not made as well as other places. We order an appetizer to split and order our entrees at the same time. Our appetizer never comes... It ends up being delivered with our entrees. Not what we wanted with an appetizer but ok. I order the cioppino, and it was tasty. He orders the steak (doesn't like seafood), and it's just ok... The steak was cooked well enough but not great, the parmesan polenta was not very good (I've made better at home) and the mushrooms were just ok (he didn't like the texture of how they were cooked). We decide on dessert, our waitress expounds on how great their pastry chef is.... It's a lie, the desserts were no better than grocery store bought desserts. Overall a disappointment based on recommendations and reviews, and their own reporting.</Review>

I would highly recommend the Pisco Punch if you like warm spices, the calamari is incredible, awesome crab cakes, and all of the entrees our party had were great. We had a layer cake dessert too that was excellent! Allow for plenty of time to enjoy a well-paced multi course meal here.<//review>

<time>1422299570925< /time>< Review>
We have a tradition of eating lunch at Scoma's when we fly in to San Fran from the east coast.  It's our first stop.  It's always been great but this past Friday night (dinner for the first time), it was a major disappointment.  Not one of the five of us enjoyed our meal.  Dry, tasteless fish and blah-broth, lazy man's cioppino. Small portions of bland, dry fish for $40.00!  I don't think so.

The staff is great and the atmosphere is cozy and fun.  Major help needed in the kitchen.  There are too many places to eat in San Fran that are excellent and unfortunately, there is little excitement or interest in eating at Scoma's again.< /Review>

<user>107376846932166977779<//user><name>Kirsty Jack< /name><Date>1508816806849<//Date><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
This place is incredible .
I don't really like seafood but I loved every single thing I ate (& I even ate a tentacle!). My other half loved seafood and loved it too.The food is fantastic and there is a lovely atmosphere.
There's a classy 60s feel inside (the waiters are in white jackets and  and just so lovely and knowledgeable). Scoma have their own boat and you can literally watch the fish come off the boat, into their processing plant and into the restaurant. You can't get fresher.
Don't let the lack of outdoor seating put you off. We arrived at sunset on a lovely night & wanted to sit outside ...... But actually a seat in the lounge by the window was incredible. We watched a lovely sunset and kept warm.< /Review>

< user_name>
Kim Daniel<//user_name>
<Time>1566401834990<//Time>< rate>
4<//rate>
< Review>
My sister and I has a late dinner here tonight. We added ourselves to the handy yelp waitlist at 8:00pm and were 17th in line.  We were instructed to be at the restaurant at 8:30pm.

We arrived late because or lyft driver was very slow but they still honored our waitlist spot.  We had a very professional and attentive waiter but not extremely personable.  I ordered the 3 fish grill (cod, salmon and halibut) and a cup of clam chowder. I loved the halibut and the salmon was above average the cold tasted a teeny bit underdone but that may have been the texture since it is a flaky fish.  She ordered calamari app, ceasar salad and a cup of clam chowder. She enjoyed everything as well but we both agreed the clam chowder was the belle of the ball.

It was a pricey meal at nearly a hundred dollars for our meals but it was a prime location and beautiful post sunset view.

While I wouldn't insist on a revisit, I have no regrets.  It was a lovely meal and a great experience.< /Review>

<username>David Smith<//username>< text>
There were 2 sides to our experience.  First we went at 2:30pm and it was very busy, unfortunately they couldn't handle it.  We had a very efficient guy filling up our drinks and bringing us bread but that wasn't the waiter, the waiter took a long, long time to take our orders, even though we had told the drink-server guy we were ready ages before.  He also made an excuse rather than just apologizing.  Then my wife was brought her chowder way before my scampi starter, this is just amateur.  Then our mains were brought before our starters had been taken away, not such a bad thing but it's a clear indication of a badly run floor and pass.  The food was tasty but also expensive.  The table next to us had complained that one of their dishes tasted very strange although the chef did come over and apologize.  Overall it was great food with very badly organized service.  Don't go when it's busy and you'll probably have a good time.< /text>

Disappointed from the high ratings it received. Ordered the trio sampler first.  The calamari was mostly tenttactes and not fried adequately.  The scallops and crab cakes on it were decent.

My seafood in marinera sauce was decent but the bartender recommend a crab cream cheese casserole dish which was subpar.

<Text>Service was fine, but not equipped to solve the food questions.

I had the Classic Crab Louie Salad (~$40). The crab was tasteless. I ate about 1/3 and gave up. Server assured me it was not frozen, but the lack of taste suggested to me it probably canned. Server suggested they may have 'washed' the crab reducing the flavor?

My friend had the Poor Man's Cioppino (~$40), which was an apt description. Lots of seafood in a thick sauce that could have been V8 juice. The brussel sprouts($9) were very good, you can't really go wrong when you add bacon to anything. Tasty bread and butter. Definitely a tourist trap, would not recommend.

Total bill a bottle of sparkling water ~$107, no alcohol. Yes, we could have sent it all back and walked out, some days you just don't have the energy for that.

Tonight we have reservations at 'Dirty Habit' and much higher expectations.<//Text><Resp>None</Resp>< Pics>

<pictures>None< /pictures><gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmapID><userid>101223343612054561388< /userid><Text>Fantastic food, great service and a welcoming atmosphere.</Text></record></dataset><record>
<resp>None<//resp><text>Love this place! Very fresh seafood, very tasty. Love the mafioso appeal. The walls filled with countless autographed celebrity photos offer amusing eye appetizers while awaiting our entrees. Best clam chowder I've ever had in The City. It's a little hidden but in a good way, likely keeping out wandering tourists or weekend hippies from chancing upon it, making it next to impossible to get a window table on a walk-in. Of all of the many eateries around San Francisco's great Wharf, Scoma's is the the only one I personally consider worthy of historical significance. Yes, Boudins began here and may still be the more popular restaurant even today, however in my opinion Boudins has grown into the Budweiser of bread. Scoma's has something no other Embarcadero restaurant has, a pulse, an identity, character, and bay city charm.  Stepping into Scoma's feels like stepping out of the city. A peaceful, quiet, sense will greet you as you enter as if time itself slows. Forwarding through time, neighboring eateries will likely fade away while Scoma's remains, gaining fame, iconic status, and historical importance. What Randy's Donuts is to LA, or what Katz Delicatessen is to Manhattan, so should Scoma's be to SF. From the cresting waves of the mighty Pacific Ocean, along California's golden coastline, a small port town filling with migrant ruffians and Forty-Niners quickly grew outward and upward. It grew across steep terrain, eventually gaining root spanning the entire Southern Peninsula. Where Giant Pacific Redwood forests once grew, now grows a mighty metropolis. A civilization so grand that Westerners know simply as, "The City," and it was here, hidden down a narrow alleyway, treaded upon by those who've come to know of it. There, built directly onto the wooden planks of a dock, nearest the point where city becomes sea, that is where you'll find it...  Scoma's. To all you soon to be first timers, you're welcome.</text><Name>Nichoulas Musselman</Name>< Pics>
None</Pics>

<user_id>104607424381319946855</user_id><user_name>Frank Eargle</user_name>< Date>
1550341564761</Date>
<Rating>5</Rating><Review>Started with a perfect Bloody Mary while waiting 45 minutes for a table.  Never has a wait been so worth it!

We had a bowl of clam chowder.  Fresh clams and organic ingredients. It was far and away the best I have had!

The entre was Pasta Diplomatica which is sort of an Alfredo white sauce.  Fresh ground pepper and fresh grated cheese added to the mix. It was a huge portion of one of the best entre's I have ever had!  Simply delicious!

The wait staff, of which there are plenty, are always there before you need them.  Always filling glasses or taking care of things, but never intruding into the meal.

It was the best meal I have had in a very long time!  Only shame was we had no room for desert.  And the desert menu was sooo tempting.

I will never come to San Francisco and miss Scoma's restaurant!</Review><pics>None< /pics><response>{'time': 1550602402346, 'text': "Hi Frank. < text>
If you think Olive Garden is fancy, then you're in for a treat.
Every thing about Scoma's is dated and out of style but screams a desperate attempt at the appearance of class. Wood paneling, conference room seating and walls of photographs of celebrities no one under 40 can name.
The food was fresh and edible, but the dishes are the very definition of boring and poorly executed by what I assume are novice chefs.
The waitstaff are, from my experience, old, slow, dressed in the typical steak house white jacket/black pants and walk with a sad, hunched, shuffling gait.
Scoma's antiquity would be endearing, if the food were not so painfully boring.</text>

< Text>
My husband & I just by chance found out about this "fabulous" place to eat. O'my is it ever wonderful, the food is spot on and the service is great. Seating can be a little tight, but since we had no reservations we couldn't complain. We had the "clams & pasta" clams braised in butter, olive oil, garlic & white wine, the roasted beet salad, and Denver Sole lightly sauteed. White wine and some yummy hot bread. Each course was served separately...we rolled out because the portions were ample enough to share. AND WE WILL RETURN!!!</Text>

I was very excited to try this place but I must say it was all hype.  The salmon was grossly over cooked to well-done (dry).  The service was horrible.  My waiter was an elderly man who had trouble hearing but that wasn't a problem.  The problem was that he visited our table once during the entire meal which was only to bring the check. <time>1534177577474<//time><user_id>111898597580333312700<//user_id>< Response>

< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< Text>
Popped in right before they were closing to grab a couple glasses of wine and some calamari. Best part of the evening is the fact we were driven here in a brand new Bentley flying spur, which was awesome, so it began with us leaving AT&T park after watching USC crush CAL (Fight On), so we proceeded to try and catch a cab, but with no luck we walked down to the  St. Regis to catch a drink and instead were greeted by the doormen offering the house car for a tour of San Francisco. We accepted.
The driver opened the doors to the beautiful car, we got in, and drove us all over the city showing us different sites and telling us a little history about each location, while my fiance and I sat in back worried that we smelled funny after our rooftop tailgate before the game with friends, but he didn't seem to notice, and we certainly weren't going to bring it up.
After he took us to a few wine bars he inquired about our lust for seafood and asked if he could suggest a spot, so we obliged and he took us to Scoma, but not before making sure a table was ready for us. We arrived and were greeted by an amazing staff and enjoyed some great bites to eat while sipping a fantastic Malbec.
The long and short of it is this, we had a great evening with great food and wine, which cannot be beat by much.< /Text>

We ordered the calamari alla pancha which was the perfect amount of spicy. It was accompanied  with a delicous corn bread that balanced out the citrus of the bed of tomato sauce. We also ordered the Pacific Black Cod drizzled in a cream sauce with seasonal vegetables and crispy potatoes. Food was fantastic. Service was amazing. Portion sizes need a bit of work. We still felt a little hungry after our meal. Still a recommended spot.<//review>

<Review>Scoma's, an SF Italian classic.  Bartop review.  Fresh seafood done well.  Skilled artisans as barkeeps.  Casey made a proper Woodford double oaked Manhattan.  The Fritto Misto appetizer had a nice touch of fresh lemon zest on the local and fresh anchovies.  The cioppino entree had a great base and a generous portion of seafood.  Overall a flawless delivery of eats and drinks.  Great service.  Retro modern digs.  Prices more than par for the segment.  Portions more than par.  A hearty 5 stars in the middle of a sea of touristy mediocrity.< /Review>< Rate>

< name>
Steve Pendleton<//name>
< date>
1294347651536< /date>
<rate>3< /rate>< Text>
This is an old restaurant that is trying to be old-style elegant. It isn't anything but old style anymore. Yes, the waiters wear white jackets, but the paneling in the dining room just looks...old. The prices are high, even for Fisherman's Wharf. Typical entree is $30+. The service is not excellent. When we arrived it was a very light Monday night crowd, but the hostess would not seat us until our friend who was parking the car arrived five minutes later. When you are really busy I can see this, but not if the restaurant is more than half empty. The quality of the food is mixed. My wife had lamb chops. Two were excellent, one was raw...and tasteless. I had swordfish in a picatta sauce. The fish was excellent, but the sauce was thin. Bottomline: there are better seafood restaurants at Fisherman's Wharf.<//Text>

<user>105085349535444602120<//user>< username>
Ashley Thoren<//username>
<date>1517080810202</date><Rate>4< /Rate>< Review>
Scoma's is a legacy, but they are just fundamentally being outgrown. Wish they would pare down the menu, update the decor a little bit, and put a little more attention on the waitstaff's skills.

Service was good, appropriately polite and attentive, but kind of clumsy in execution for the intended ambience. E.g. reaching over other guests to serve plates and grate cheese, or forgetting which plate goes where, or just generally awkward interruptions in table conversation and rushed ordering. To be fair, we sat at the bar tables instead of waiting for our reservation.

Food was good but not great. My Bolognese was obviously fresh but the papardelle was sticking and the sauce wasn't much to write home about. Table bread was cold.

I recognize that I'm likely being picky on the details, but based upon the price of the meal, my expectations were higher.

Not 5 stars, but otherwise a good meal and quality service.</Review>

< Text>
Zagat must be slipping... apparently a 25 means: salads made from brown, wilted, store-bought pre-prepared mixes that sat in the back of the fridge too long, mediocre wine selections and crab so overcooked you have to chew on it like a strap of leather.  If you want better seafood, go to a Red Lobster.  Scoma's was singularly terrible in that regard.  No complaints about the atmosphere or the waitstaff though, they did a great job.  It was too bad that when they asked me how everything was, the only nice thing I could say was that the bread was great (and it was).< /Text>

< Text>
Ordered bistro filet, wagyu sirloin cut with smashed potatoes, and raw sliced carrots. Presentation wasn't great. Carrots were right; raw and edible. Smashed potatoes were right and cooked well. The 9 oz filet by no means looked like 9oz it was dished up cut in half. The temperature of the steak was more like medium than what was ordered which was supposed to be medium rare. The waiter Chris was nice and courteous.</Text>

<userid>105085349535444602120<//userid>< user_name>
Ashley Thoren</user_name>
<time>1517080810202</time>< Rating>

< Review>
Scoma's is a legacy, but they are just fundamentally being outgrown. Wish they would pare down the menu, update the decor a little bit, and put a little more attention on the waitstaff's skills.

Service was good, appropriately polite and attentive, but kind of clumsy in execution for the intended ambience. E.g. reaching over other guests to serve plates and grate cheese, or forgetting which plate goes where, or just generally awkward interruptions in table conversation and rushed ordering. To be fair, we sat at the bar tables instead of waiting for our reservation.

Food was good but not great. My Bolognese was obviously fresh but the papardelle was sticking and the sauce wasn't much to write home about. Table bread was cold.

I recognize that I'm likely being picky on the details, but based upon the price of the meal, my expectations were higher.

Not 5 stars, but otherwise a good meal and quality service.<//Review>

113861163979876786447< /user>
<gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34<//gmapID><Name>Todd Hammond< /Name>< Text>
Walked in off the street and had about a 15 minute wait to be seated. It was a fairly busy day so there was no place to sit while we waited. They use a texting service to let you know your table is ready, so we just walked around outside.

We started with the fried calamari and it was very good - they cooked it differently then we've ever had it before - big pieces (great dipping sauce too).

After the calamari, we were all actually pretty full so we weren't as hungry for dinner as we would have liked. We had swordfish, shrimp in egg batter and ahi. All were cooked well and tasted good, but not amazing.

Great views from the restaurant, super service, will come back to try the clam chowder!< /Text>

< text>
Skip this place. It was recommended to us and we went to this classic and long-established restaurant. A short wait at the bar and we were eating. The service from Jose was friendly, but the food was at best average, and the prices are high ($110 (incl tip) for dinner for 2, no apps or dessert and 2 beer/wine each). The fresh wild salmon was utterly unremarkable, slightly overcooked and with little flavor (I could have easily done better at home any number of ways), and the pasta with sausage was OK but overwhelmed by black olives. Perhaps other things on the menu are better, but at these prices I can't see coming back to eat my way through the menu to find something better than average. Spend your money elsewhere.
Service: A
Quality of Food: C-
Value for Money; F< /text>

<Review>I had black cod with lemon aoli over smashed potatoes. Van, our waiter (maybe Dan - older gentleman from Chicago) told me it was good, gave me a description, and I, a lady who doesn't like strong tasting fish, LOVED IT!!!!  We started with soup, my husband had clam chowder, I had the lobster bisque. Excellent start to a wonderful meal. We finished with the 7 layer cake; chocolatey, hazelnutty, creamy, crunchy, but not over sweet. The perfect end to a perfect meal! The only part of the meal not extraordinary was the bread - just ordinary bread that was cold in the center. Thank you Scomas for an absolutely delicious meal. Parking is valet - when you start down Al Scomas Way, go over the bridge, make the turn and the valets take it from there. No charge (we tipped).<//Review></record></dataset><record>

115685129152446132340<//UserId.>
<name>Diana Duebelbeis<//name>< date>
1492801649537<//date>
<Rate>2<//Rate>< text>
This is an "Old School" Italian Seafood Restaurant.....perfect.....our two most favorite foods (Italian and Seafood) and we LOVE anything "Old School."
Upon entering.....you immediately get the 60's vibe.  We went for My 50th Birthday lunch....so had every intention of hanging for a bit with a bottle of wine and of course some Birthday dessert.....all those things that really help to run up the bill....and we didn't care one bit. We were seated in the back upper level. The dining room was not very big and they made sure to seat everyone in one section so it was hard to have any real conversation. We ordered a cocktail while looking over the menu. We both decided on Seafood. My husband ordered the Salmon and I ordered the Dungeness Crab Salad, with a bottle of wine to come w/the meal. Our lunches were brought to the table and as soon as the server walked away, my husband looked at his fish and said "this doesn't look good"  I looked at the fish and could see what he was talking about.....it looked so dried out. He took a few bites and it was awful. My salad was ok....it was supposed to be shelled crab. Of course every bite I took, I had to pull shell out of my mouth. Shelled=Means no shell or cartilage. I can understand a bite or two w/shell but this was ridiculous. The server forgot the wine and we were so glad.....because we were so unhappy that we just wanted to get out of there.  We couldn't believe this is what was served for the price. Our bill was was $125......before tip.  We didn't bother to send the food back because we figured everything was going to come out just as bad.  So totally disappointed! I think the chef needs more training or they need to have better quality control. Would NEVER recommend this establishment.</text>

<Time>1591970376303<//Time>< resp>
{'time': 1592014083583, 'text': "Yuri, if you are referring to the issue FV Pioneer has brought up, please know Scoma's has long been one of, if not the biggest supporters of the local fishing fleet, including FV Pioneer. Below is a statement from the Port of San Francisco outlining the facts of the situation:\nThis is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales.\n\nThank you for your interest and please contact the Port of San Francisco if you have any questions regarding this situation."}</resp>

<Review>(Translated by Google) A classic Italian seafood restaurant on the water in San Francisco. They have a great selection of fish, seafood, crab and a single steak.
The dishes are on the expensive end - $ 35-40 for a main course, but the portions are large so you can plentifully settle for a lunch. We got Linguine alla Vongole and Pasta Putanesca. The wine is pricey and OK. The beers are cheaper. Their double IPA is fantastic. Try a cocktail while you wait. The lemon kiss (Bacio al Limone) is excellent.
The service is classic, good and attentive.
Can be recommended if you can afford it.
